{
  "general_skills": [
    {
      "name": "clarify-ambiguous-requests",
      "description": "Use when the user's request is ambiguous, under-specified, or could be interpreted in multiple ways.",
      "content": "## Clarify Ambiguous Requests\n\nWhen the task is unclear, do not guess — ask one focused clarifying question before proceeding.\n\n**Process:**\n1. Identify the single most important ambiguity.\n2. Ask exactly one targeted question.\n3. Wait for the answer before proceeding.\n\n**Examples of ambiguity:**\n- Vague time references ('soon', 'later')\n- Unclear scope ('fix the code', 'improve performance')\n- Missing context or prerequisites"
    },
    {
      "name": "structured-step-by-step-reasoning",
      "description": "Use for any problem that involves multiple steps, tradeoffs, or non-trivial logic.",
      "content": "## Structured Step-by-Step Reasoning\n\nFor non-trivial problems, reason explicitly before giving the final answer.\n\n**Process:**\n1. **Restate** the core question or problem.\n2. **Identify** key sub-problems or components.\n3. **Analyze** each sub-problem with intermediate reasoning.\n4. **Verify** intermediate results where possible.\n5. **Synthesize** the final answer from components.\n\n**When to use:**\n- Multi-step calculations or derivations\n- Architecture or design decisions\n- Debugging complex issues\n- Trade-off analysis"
    },
    {
      "name": "error-handling-best-practices",
      "description": "Use when writing code that handles errors, exceptions, or failure modes.",
      "content": "## Error Handling Best Practices\n\n**Principles:**\n1. **Fail fast** on programmer errors (use panic/assert)\n2. **Fail gracefully** on recoverable errors\n3. **Log context** — include request ID, user ID, stack trace\n4. **Never swallow errors** silently\n\n**Patterns:**\n- Wrap errors with context: `fmt.Errorf(\"process request: %w\", err)`\n- Use sentinel errors for recoverable cases\n- Return errors as values, handle at appropriate layer\n- Use error types for structured error data"
    },
    {
      "name": "security-first-mindset",
      "description": "Use when handling user input, authentication, authorization, or sensitive data.",
      "content": "## Security-First Mindset\n\n**Input Validation:**\n- Never trust user-supplied input\n- Validate type, length, format at system boundaries\n- Sanitize before rendering or storing\n\n**Authentication & Authorization:**\n- Verify authorization on every protected endpoint\n- Use principle of least privilege\n- Rotate secrets regularly\n\n**Secrets Management:**\n- No hardcoded passwords, API keys, or tokens\n- Use environment variables or secret managers\n- Log secrets never, not even partially\n\n**Injection Prevention:**\n- Parameterize all database queries\n- Sanitize HTML/markdown before rendering\n- Validate URLs before following redirects"
    },
    {
      "name": "performance-considerations",
      "description": "Use when optimizing code for speed, memory, or throughput.",
      "content": "## Performance Considerations\n\n**Before Optimizing:**\n1. Measure — use profiling to find actual bottlenecks\n2. Identify the critical path\n3. Set measurable performance goals\n\n**Common Patterns:**\n- **Caching**: Cache expensive computations, respect TTLs\n- **Batching**: Batch I/O operations (DB, API calls)\n- **Async**: Use goroutines/async for independent operations\n- **Pooling**: Reuse connections, workers, buffers\n\n**Memory:**\n- Avoid allocations in hot paths\n- Use sync.Pool for frequently allocated objects\n- Stream large data instead of buffering"
    },
    {
      "name": "api-design-principles",
      "description": "Use when designing REST APIs, gRPC services, or internal interfaces.",
      "content": "## API Design Principles\n\n**Consistency:**\n- Use consistent naming conventions (REST: nouns, gRPC: VerbNoun)\n- Standard error formats across all endpoints\n- Version from day one\n\n**Usability:**\n- Provide sensible defaults\n- Be generous with what you accept, strict with what you return\n- Include documentation and examples\n\n**Idempotency:**\n- Design for retry-safety\n- Use idempotency keys for state-changing operations\n\n**Versioning:**\n- URL versioning for REST: `/v1/`, `/v2/`\n- Package versioning for libraries\n- Maintain backward compatibility when possible"
    }
  ],
  "task_specific_skills": {
    "coding": [
      {
        "name": "secure-code-review",
        "description": "Use when reviewing or writing code that handles user input, authentication, or file I/O.",
        "content": "## Secure Code Review Checklist\n\n**Input Validation:**\n- [ ] All user inputs are validated before use\n- [ ] Type coercion is explicit\n- [ ] Length limits enforced\n- [ ] Special characters sanitized\n\n**Authentication:**\n- [ ] Authorization checked on every protected route\n- [ ] Session tokens are secure\n- [ ] Passwords hashed with appropriate algorithm\n\n**Data Protection:**\n- [ ] No secrets in code or logs\n- [ ] Sensitive data encrypted at rest\n- [ ] HTTPS enforced in production\n\n**Error Handling:**\n- [ ] Errors don't leak implementation details\n- [ ] Failures don't expose stack traces"
      },
      {
        "name": "code-documentation",
        "description": "Use when writing documentation for code, APIs, or systems.",
        "content": "## Code Documentation Guidelines\n\n**For Functions:**\n```go\n// FuncName does X with Y, returning Z.\n//\n// It handles edge cases by doing W.\n//\n// Example:\n//   result, err := FuncName(ctx, input)\n//   if err != nil {\n//       return nil, fmt.Errorf(\" FuncName: %w\", err)\n//   }\nfunc FuncName(ctx context.Context, input Input) (Output, error)\n```\n\n**For Packages:**\n- Document the package's purpose in doc.go\n- List main types and their relationships\n- Include usage examples"
      }
    ],
    "math": [
      {
        "name": "show-all-steps",
        "description": "Use when the user asks a math problem, derivation, or quantitative analysis question.",
        "content": "## Show All Steps\n\n1. **State** the knowns and what you're solving for.\n2. **Write** out every algebraic step explicitly.\n3. **Include** units throughout.\n4. **Verify** by substituting back.\n\n**Notation:**\n- Use standard mathematical notation\n- Define all variables before use\n- Show intermediate results with units\n\n**Example format:**\n```\nGiven: v₀ = 10 m/s, a = 2 m/s², t = 5 s\nFind: v₁\n\nv₁ = v₀ + at\n   = 10 + (2)(5)\n   = 10 + 10\n   = 20 m/s\n\nVerify: ✓ (correct dimensions, reasonable magnitude)"
      }
    ],
    "debugging": [
      {
        "name": "systematic-debugging",
        "description": "Use when debugging a bug, crash, or unexpected behavior.",
        "content": "## Systematic Debugging Process\n\n1. **Reproduce** — Can you consistently reproduce the bug?\n2. **Isolate** — Find the minimal case that triggers it\n3. **Hypothesize** — What's the most likely cause?\n4. **Test** — Verify or refute the hypothesis\n5. **Fix** — Implement the smallest fix possible\n6. **Verify** — Confirm the bug is gone\n7. **Prevent** — Add a test to catch this in the future\n\n**Tools:**\n- Logs: Look for ERROR, WARN before the crash\n- Traces: Find the span where things went wrong\n- Metrics: Check for anomalies in resource usage\n- Reproducer: Create a minimal test case"
      }
    ],
    "writing": [
      {
        "name": "concise-technical-writing",
        "description": "Use when writing technical documentation, emails, or explanations.",
        "content": "## Concise Technical Writing\n\n**Principles:**\n1. **Lead with the point** — Put conclusions first\n2. **Use active voice** — 'The system processes' not 'The system is processed'\n3. **Be specific** — Use numbers, names, not 'many', 'some'\n4. **Cut filler** — Remove 'in order to', 'that', 'just'\n\n**Structure:**\n- **Subject/Verb first**: 'The API returns 200' not 'A 200 response is returned'\n- **Short sentences**: One idea per sentence\n- **Lists for steps**: Use numbered lists for sequences\n- **Tables for comparisons**: Use tables for structured data\n\n**Example:**\n❌ 'In order to ensure that the request is processed correctly...'\n✅ 'To process the request correctly...'"
      }
    ]
  }
}
